Predicting Crime at UMD¶

For our final project we've decided to predict crimes at the University of Maryland, College Park in order to inform UMPD of better police allocation for the next year. Predicting crime hotspots at certain times can help with positioning of police patrols, letting them get to crime scenes faster and, by extension, deter offenders. Faster response times will allow victims to get help quicker and will allow less time for perpetrators to break the law and less time for them to escape.

This will keep campus safer and give students - especially those of them living on campus - peace of mind. Keeping students safe makes UMD a more appealing option for prospective students and allows current students an environment in which they can focus on studying and building their future rather than on having to worry about keeping themselves safe.

Part 1: Gathering the Data¶

We decided to grab the on-campus crime data for 2021 and 2022. Below we scrape the data by month from the umpd website and format it into one data frame for each of the years. We also gather data from the safety notices for each year.

Once we gather the data we do an initial formatting of the column names and add a couple columns to the safety dataframes for later. We were able to get all of the months from 2021 but there was no data for July of 2022 or December (likely because it's too early into the month).

The monthly reports are concatenated into one dataframe for each year for further processing to match the processing done on the safety notices. Each of the months' data is formatted the same so they can just be combined into one larger dataframe.

In [ ]:

data21 = pd.concat([jan21, feb21, mar21, apr21, may21, jun21, jul21, aug21, sep21, oct21, nov21, dec21], axis = 0)

The web tables stored the locations in the row after each incident so the first loop takes that location and puts it in the same row as the incident. The second loop takes the rows with the incidents and adds them to a new dataframe for each year. After this is done, we concatenate the safety notices to the end of the data frame.

Many of the incidents in the 2021 data had similar names such that they could be encapsulated by another category. For example different classifications involving fraud all had their classifications redefined as simply fraud. Combining these classifications into a broader one makes the analysis simpler since we have less specific classifications to worry about, which then helps generalize our results. We went ahead and manually combined the classifications by searching for key terms in the more specific classifications.

In [ ]:
# reducing number of duplicate incidents (since reiterated)

for row in crime21.iterrows():
  if "Theft" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Theft"
  elif "Weapon" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Weapon Law Violation"
  elif "Assault" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Assault"
  elif "Vandalism" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Vandalism"
  elif "Fraud" in row[1].classification or "Scam" in row[1].classification or "Counterfeit" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Fraud"
  elif "Rape" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Rape"
  elif "Fondling" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Fondling"
  elif "Trespassing" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Trespassing"
  elif "Hate" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Hate Bias Incident"
  elif "Burglar" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Burglary"
  elif "Stole" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Theft"
  elif "Drug" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Drug/Narcotic Violation"
  elif "Driving Under Influence" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Driving Under Influence"
  elif "Other" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Other"
  elif "Peeping" in row[1].classification:
    row[1].classification = "Voyeur Incident"

All of the time and date related columns are parsed using regular expressions to get an array of values to be parsed in datetime constructors. We also created dummy columns for the date and time of the crime and the date of the report so that we could better test our operations without risk of losing data during parsing in case the parsing was incorrect.

The first loop here iterates over the 2022 data and takes the arrays from the regex and uses the appropriate index to create datetime.date and datetime.time objects instead of strings. This will make it easier to work with the data so we can extract a specific date or time instead of having to work with more regex or converting strings to ints. The second loop does the same process for the 2021 data.

In [ ]:
# getting date, time and report time into the new columns

for row in crime.iterrows():
  if row[1].date_time[0] == '':
    crime.loc[row[1].name, "date"] = dt.date((2022), int(row[1].date_time[1]), int(row[1].date_time[2]))
  else:
    crime.loc[row[1].name, "date"] = np.nan

  if len(row[1].date_time) > 1 and row[1].date_time[5] is not None:
    crime.loc[row[1].name, "time"] = dt.time(int(row[1].date_time[5]), int(row[1].date_time[6]), 0)
  else:
    crime.loc[row[1].name, "time"] = np.nan

  crime.loc[row[1].name, "report"] = dt.date((2022), int(row[1].report_date[1]), int(row[1].report_date[2]))

for row in crime21.iterrows():
  if row[1].date_time[0] == '':
    crime21.loc[row[1].name, "date"] = dt.date((2021), int(row[1].date_time[1]), int(row[1].date_time[2]))
  else:
    crime21.loc[row[1].name, "date"] = np.nan

  if len(row[1].date_time) > 1 and len(row[1].date_time) > 6 and row[1].date_time[5] is not None and row[1].date_time[5].isnumeric():
    crime21.loc[row[1].name, "time"] = dt.time(int(row[1].date_time[5]), int(row[1].date_time[6]), 0)
  else:
    crime21.loc[row[1].name, "time"] = np.nan

  if row[1].report_date[1].isnumeric() and row[1].report_date[2].isnumeric():
    crime21.loc[row[1].name, "report"] = dt.date((2021), int(row[1].report_date[1]), int(row[1].report_date[2]))

After visualizing the number of crimes recorded by a couple variables (classification and location) we wanted to start seeing how different variables interacted. We began thinking of what plots we could use to make meaningful conclusions and what variables we had that would be useful to compare. Our first graph compares the classification of each crime to the month in which it was committed. Without much technical analysis there doesn't seem to be too much correlation between classification and date, although it is interesting to see a drop in overall crime from around may to late august of 2022.

Taking a bit of a closer look at the grapph it does seem like indecent exposures are more common during the UMD fall semester, while dating violence, stalking, theft, and harassment are all more common during the spring semester.

Neural Network¶

In order to classify what crimes will appear in 2023 we attempted to use a Neural Network to go through the data. To set up the data we take the classifications of the crimes as the target data andn format the report/date/time to be more understandable for the algorithm.

In [ ]:
random.seed(20)

copy = pd.concat([crime21, crime], axis = 0)
combined = copy
y_train = pd.get_dummies(copy["classification"])

copy["report"] = copy["report"].apply(lambda x : 10000*x.year + 100*x.month + x.day)
copy["date"] = copy["date"].apply(lambda x : 10000*x.year + 100*x.month + x.day if isinstance(x, dt.date) else 0)
copy["time"] = copy["time"].apply(lambda x : 60*x.hour + x.minute if isinstance(x, dt.time) else 0)

copy = copy.drop(["classification", "disposition"], axis=1)
copy = pd.get_dummies(copy, columns=["loc"])

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(copy, y_train, test_size=.2)

We started with three layers for the neural network but after inadequate results decided to add another. As can be seen from the output, the loss isn't terrible but the accuracy is very poor.

In [ ]:
model = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
  #tf.keras.layers.Normalization(axis=-1), #Normalization layer
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(959, input_dim=96, activation='tanh', kernel_initializer='he_uniform'), # Number of input features
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(700, activation='softmax'),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(497, activation='softmax'),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(41, activation='softmax') # Number of Output classes
])

model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01, momentum=0.9), metrics=['accuracy'])
model.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=10)

Arima¶

We came across a model called ARIMA while looking for something to analyze a time series to possibly predict when crimes would occur. the first stat to using it is to look at the autocorrelation of the time data across both of the years. We first look at a series of graphs to determine specific parameters we need to actually implement the model.

In [ ]:

#temp = temp['report']
temp = copy.time
# trying to find the d value so we're plotting autocorrelation for report date
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf
plot_acf(temp)
Out[ ]:
In [ ]:
# taking the 1st order difference because our graph was eh
f = plt.figure()
ax1 = f.add_subplot(121)
ax1.set_title('1st Order Differencing')
ax1.plot(temp.diff())

ax2 = f.add_subplot(122)
plot_acf(temp.diff().dropna(), ax=ax2)
plt.show()

We used the Augmented Dickey-Fuler test to determine which differential to use in the model (0, 1st, or 2nd). The aim is to use the test with a p-value below our desired threshold while still being closest to it. In other words it's ok for a test to be above the desired p-value as long as it is closer than the other tests. Out of all the p-values we had we decided the best would be the 3.85e-10 so we decided on using the 0th differential.

In [ ]:
# Augmented Dickey-Fuller test

from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
#normal
result = adfuller(temp.dropna())
print('p-value: ', result[1])

# 1st diff
result = adfuller(temp.diff().dropna())
print('p-value: ', result[1])

# 2nd diff
result = adfuller(temp.diff().diff().dropna())
print('p-value: ', result[1])

The originall parameters we came up with for using with the ARIMA model were p = 1, d = 1, and q = 1, although using those parameters caused an error in the model We did get the model to work after altering the values but we later decided to go back and slightly change the format of our data which resulted in different graphs and different p-values. From these new values we decided to use (1, 0, 2) as our input values for "order"

Conclusion¶

Here is our main takeaway from this data:

1 - The most common crimes are Vandalism, Noise Violation, and Alcohol Violation across both years, with Theft being very common only in 2021

2 - Most of the crimes seem to be committed in the north western parts of campus, notably Elkton and Elicott Hall seem to have a decent amount of theft

3 - Most crime seems to take place during the semester, with certain crimes being more common during the fall semester but none being more common during the spring semester

According to our results, it appears that since the incidents occur mainly in the north of campus nearer to the Denton Quad, it would be beneficial for campus police to patrol closer to that part of campus and be ready to head there more than other areas on campus. This will lower response times and help to keep the campus safer.
